²42· Vectigales aut stipendiarios. The distinction between these two words is this; ‘vectigales’ denotes those conquered nations who paid their tribute to Rome in the form of taxes or imposts, whether paid in kind, as the Sicilian decimae or tithe of their corn, or in money3 ‘stipendiarii’ those who had to pay a fixed sum annually. Wherc the words are used separately‚ they are not always confined to their accurate meaning. In Livy 21. 41, Hannibal is spoken of with rhetorical exaggeration by Scipio as ‘vectigalis stipendiariusque et servus populi Romani a patre relictus.’
